comment.diff_hunk:
@@ -0,0 +1,135 @@
+# Multi-stage build: First the full builder image:
+
+ARG INSTALLDIR_OPENSSL=/opt/openssl32
+ARG INSTALLDIR_LIBOQS=/opt/liboqs
+
+# liboqs build type variant; maximum portability of image:
+ARG LIBOQS_BUILD_DEFINES="-DOQS_DIST_BUILD=ON"
+
+# Define the degree of parallelism when building the image; leave the number away only if you know what you are doing
+ARG MAKE_DEFINES="-j 8"
+
+ARG SIG_ALG="dilithium3"
+
+FROM ubuntu as buildopenssl
+# Take in all global args
+ARG INSTALLDIR_OPENSSL
+ARG INSTALLDIR_LIBOQS
+ARG LIBOQS_BUILD_DEFINES
+ARG MAKE_DEFINES
+ARG SIG_ALG
+
+LABEL version="1"
+ENV DEBIAN_FRONTEND noninteractive
+
+RUN apt update && apt upgrade -y
+
+# Get all software packages required for builing openssl
+RUN apt install -y build-essential clang libtool make gcc ninja-build cmake libtool wget git
+
+# get current openssl sources
+RUN mkdir /optbuild && cd /optbuild && git clone --depth 1 --branch master https://github.com/openssl/openssl.git
+
+# build OpenSSL3
+WORKDIR /optbuild/openssl
+RUN LDFLAGS="-Wl,-rpath -Wl,${INSTALLDIR_OPENSSL}/lib64" ./config shared --prefix=${INSTALLDIR_OPENSSL} && \
+    make ${MAKE_DEFINES} && make install && if [ -d ${INSTALLDIR_OPENSSL}/lib64 ]; then ln -s ${INSTALLDIR_OPENSSL}/lib64 ${INSTALLDIR_OPENSSL}/lib; fi && if [ -d ${INSTALLDIR_OPENSSL}/lib ]; then ln -s ${INSTALLDIR_OPENSSL}/lib ${INSTALLDIR_OPENSSL}/lib64; fi

> Is there an outside chance that both /opt/openssl32/lib and /opt/openssl32/lib64 will exist as directories?

No: OpenSSL creates either, not both. I still don't understand the logic which when.

Creates an image for interop testing at https://github.com/IETF-Hackathon/pqc-certificates:
- Based on ubuntu
- builds `openssl` (master)
- latest `liboqs`
- `oqsprovider` with all algorithms and [NOPUBKEY_IN_PRIVKEY](https://github.com/open-quantum-safe/oqs-provider/blob/main/CONFIGURE.md#nopubkey_in_privkey) set

Note: Not added to CI: Worthwhile? Current image deposited at https://hub.docker.com/repository/docker/openquantumsafe/oqs-ossl3/general (:interop)

comment.body:
I believe that `sh` also supports the `-z` operator, so checking to see if `KEM_ALG` is set can be done in the same way for both.

Taking a closer look, I don't think the `==` operator is specified by the `sh` standard, so lines 5-7 in the `sh` script might not actually be doing anything at the moment. (`sh` complains about an unexpected operator on my local machine, for instance.)
